NEW BUSINESS:
- Discussion regarding Pickleball Courts at Fenton City Park. Mary Heinemann shared that she has received inquiries for consideration of outdoor pickleball courts. She expressed if this is something the Committee is interested in information for grants could be obtained and construction expense considered for the 2024 Capital Projects budget.

Alderman Huels shared she recently personally inquired on cost for an outdoor pickleball court. The estimate was $100,000 to $150,000 (one surface area/two (2) courts).

Public Works Director Dan Howard suggested if considered, a location to be constructed could be the area where the horseshoe pits are currently located in Fenton City Park. There are nearby amenities such as a water fountain and electrical connection if lighting is desired. He further suggested concrete courts due to flooding concerns for longevity and maintenance.

Phillip Van Cleave inquired if the usage of courts would be free or would there be a rental fee. Mary Heinemann shared after research most courts are free/first come first serve. Public Works Director Dan Howard shared that unless courts were fenced and locked, rental would be difficult to enforce.

After discussion, Mary Heinemann made a motion for the Public Works Director to explore costs for Pickleball Courts in Fenton City Park (constructed of concrete in the area where the horseshoe pits are currently located) with striping and the option for fencing and bring back to the Parks and Recreation Committee for further review. Mike Abbott seconded the motion.

5 Ayes; 0 Nays, 2 Absent, 0 Abstain: Motion APPROVED by voice vote.

- Discussion regarding proposed information signage in City Parks. Staff has been reviewing the information signage in each park and is in the process of gathering quotes for the replacement of each sign. The goal is to have uniform informational signage in each park that, as requested by the Parks and Recreation Committee, is more concise (less cluttered) more visible at night (reflective) and ensures the park hours are readily visible.

Based on the above, staff provided proposed verbiage for each sign that was available for review. The intent is to have the name of the park and the hours of operation (and speed limits, if any) the most visible information, while providing the basic rules within the park (that are not already posted elsewhere in the park). The replacement signs could be metal, similar to Valiant and Riverside, with reflective material, at approximately the same size as the existing signs (48" x 36"). Most likely all signposts will also need to be replaced. Funding for new informational signage in the parks is in the 2023 Capital Improvement Plan.

If the Committee agrees with the verbiage proposal, staff will have a sign company assist in creating the overall design and provide an estimate for the replacements.

Mike Abbott suggested replacing Fabick Park map sign also. City Administrator Nikki Finkbiner asked Committee members to take an inventory/survey of the signs in their assigned parks to assist staff.

After discussion, Phillip Van Cleave made a motion approve new informational signs in City Parks, containing the information (signs to be in a similar design as the informational sign in Fabick Nature Preserve, be constructed of a heavier, reflective metal material, at an approximate cost of $185 per sign with a total of nine (9) signs). Mary Heinemann seconded the motion.

5 Ayes; 0 Nays, 2 Absent, 0 Abstain: Motion APPROVED by voice vote.

- Discussion regarding invasive species control in Fabick Nature Preserve. As recommended by the Committee and approved by the Board, staff has begun the application process for invasive species removal in the Fabick Nature Preserve under the Missouri Department of Conservation (MDC) Community Conservation Assistance Program.

As a reminder, the application for the grant is revolving throughout the year (no deadline); however, the maximum funding available per project is $49,000, with the City providing a minimum 50% cost-share. In order to apply for the grant, the City must have a cost estimate for the overall scope of work to be completed.

Based on the above, staff met with a certified arborist/contractor (Native Landscape Solutions) that has worked on such projects with the MDC and can assist in developing a plan that will assist in the cost estimate. It was noted during the site visit that the overall scope of the project will most likely require the City to phase the project out over a few years, which will require the City to apply for multiple grant rounds through the MDC.

In order for the contractor to provide a cost estimate, the City will need to determine priority areas within the park and the method in which removal will be implemented. A plan that was provided by the contractor for review, consideration, and discussion was available for review.

After discussion, Mike Abbott made a motion to approve for Staff to apply for the MDC Community Conservation Assistance Program funds for the Fabick Nature Preserve utilizing invasive species removal/native habitat plan presented by Staff with the priority being invasive species control. Gary Johnson seconded the motion.

5 Ayes; 0 Nays, 2 Absent, 0 Abstain: Motion APPROVED by voice vote.

